    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Transport Agency Ignored The Voice of the 'Little Guy'</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Dennis Fagan letter on June 25 article holds widening roads was not majority opinion among volunteer committee members who offered input on Long Island Transportation Plan 2000 (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>So after a $7 million study, we get more of the same -- more asphalt, more traffic, more ozone-alert days. If our leaders cannot buck the car culture, why do they bother to ask the public's opinion?</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>So after a $7 million study, we get more of the same -- more asphalt, more traffic, more ozone-alert days. If our leaders cannot buck the car culture, why do they bother to ask the public's opinion?</p>
        <p>The predictable conclusion of the plan to widen roads is an insult to members of the public who took the trouble to take part in the study. As a member of the public committee, I can tell you that widening roads was not a majority opinion. People who attended had many promising (and some not so promising) proposals, but very few seemed to favor more of the same.</p>
        <p>DENNIS FAGAN  East Moriches</p>
      </block>
